2026-04-21 01:38:03 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['internal indicator lamp (small bulb) in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show the supply, control module, relay contacts, series diode, and main external lamp receive a steady ~12 V with correct polarity, even during the brief 0.5 s intervals when the visible main lamp is reported OFF. The control relay output does not vary with the flicker, and the diode output to the lamps is also steady. This rules out oscillation or supply interruption and localizes the symptom inside the load module, downstream of the diode.\n\nThe test on the load module shows the internal indicator lamp consistently has ~11 V across it and is lit, including during the intervals when the main lamp appears off. That implies that current through the lamp branch is present and the circuit is actually energized continuously. Therefore, the periodic apparent turning off of the external lamp cannot be due to loss of electrical power to the lamp; instead it must be due to the way the indicator lamp and main lamp interact optically and thermally.\n\nGiven the problem statement that the main lamp itself is not faulty (confirmed by prior replacement test), the only remaining component that could create an apparent 0.5 s dark period while current still flows is the internal indicator lamp: if it is excessively bright or wrongly specified (e.g., too high wattage, mis‑rated filament, or installed in a way that its light leaks out and swamps the main lamp or activates the ambient light sensor via reflections), it could cause the observed flicker without any electrical anomaly.\n\nThus the most plausible root cause is a defective or incorrect internal indicator lamp in the load module. Replacing or correcting this small bulb should remove the apparent 20 s / 0.5 s cycling while leaving the control and power‑supply behavior unchanged.'
