2026-04-21 01:38:14 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module common return / negative wiring', 'load module internal lamp return connections'] hypothesis_explanation='All tests show a rock‑steady 12 V supply from the power module through the ambient sensor module to the load module input, and the series diode in the load module drops a constant ~0.8 V with about 11 V present at the lamp supply node even during the 0.5 s ‘off’ events. The internal indicator lamp node also remains at ~11 V relative to the module return. These measurements exclude faults in the battery, control module, relay, timing/sensitivity networks, series diode, and both lamps themselves (they have already been replaced and tested good).\n\nThe only remaining way for the visible main lamp to periodically extinguish while the internal measurements remain steady is an intermittent or high‑impedance connection in the load module’s common return (negative) side for the lamp circuit. A poor solder joint, cracked PCB trace, or loose wire on the lamp return can momentarily open under thermal or mechanical conditions, causing the main lamp current to drop to nearly zero for about 0.5 s, while the measurement reference (taken at a slightly different ground point or via a meter with high input impedance) still shows nearly normal voltages. Because the internal indicator lamp is wired in parallel but may return via a slightly different path or more solid connection, it can remain lit even when the main lamp’s specific return path opens.\n\nTherefore, the root cause is most likely an intermittent/open connection on the load module’s negative/common return wiring associated with the lamp(s), rather than a fault in the active components or the lamps themselves. Repair would involve reworking or replacing the load module return wiring and solder joints for the lamp circuits.'
